mask.name: Retransmission
mask.text: Indicates the packet is a retransmission. Cannot be paired with 0x00000002.

mask.name: EncryptedChecksum
mask.text: Indicates the checksum has been encrypted. Cannot be paired with 0x00000001.

mask.name: BlobFragments
mask.text: Indicates the packet contains blob fragments.

mask.name: ServerSwitch
mask.text: Sent by the server to confirm connection to the new server.

mask.name: SockAddr
mask.text: Seems to send a socket address structure. Not sure if this was used.

mask.name: Unknown1
mask.text: Maybe a response to 0x200? Carries no data.

mask.name: Referral
mask.text: Sent by the server when directing the client to connect to a different IP/Port

mask.name: NegativeAck
mask.text: Sent when requesting a retransmission, indicating we did not receive one or more sequence IDs

mask.name: EmptyAck
mask.text: Sent if retransmission is not possible, asking us to clear those sequence IDs out of our pending list.

mask.name: PositiveAck
mask.text: Sent to confirm receiving sequences IDs up to the one provided

mask.name: Disconnect
mask.text: Sent when disconnecting from a game server (not from the game, but perhaps while switching from one server to a different one)

mask.name: LoginRequest
mask.text: Sent by the client when logging into the game.

mask.name: ServerSwitchRequest
mask.text: Sent by the client to start connecting to the location provided in the referral.

mask.name: ConnectRequest
mask.text: Sent by the server to indicate the client can connect.

mask.name: ConnectResponse
mask.text: Sent by the client to confirm

mask.name: NetError
mask.text: Some kind of network error message

mask.name: CloseConnection
mask.text: Sent when ending a connection to a world server

mask.name: CICMDCommand
mask.text: Sent by the client. Some kind of command from the client. Client seems to only send noOp. Sent every 220 intervals.

mask.name: TimeSync
mask.text: Transmits high resolution time for gear detection.

mask.name: EchoRequest
mask.text: Sent by the client. Ping request.

mask.name: EchoResponse
mask.text: Sent by the server. Pong response.

mask.name: Flow
mask.text: Both. Sent each time the interval changes, providing the bytes recieved during that interval period.

type.name: Packet
type.text: Basic packet structure for all communication packets between the client and server.

field.name: header
field.text: Bitmask identifiying the content/options on the packet

field.name: checksum
field.text: CRC value for verifying the content of the packet

field.name: recId
field.text: Recipient id, must be less than or equal to 0x100

field.name: interval
field.text: Something to do with flow management. 1 interval seems to be 1/2 a second. Client sends TimeSynch and EchoRequest every 6 intervals. It sends CICMD every 220.

field.name: dataLen
field.text: Length of data in the packet, excluding this header

field.name: iteration
field.text: An id for the current session with a particular world server. Will increase each time we leave and then return to a particular server, receiving a new ConnectRequest.

member.name: fragments
member.text: List of fragments. Variable length, fragment header defines the length.

member.name: sequenceID
member.text: For non-ephemeral messages, this appears to just count up. For ephemeral messages, this stays the same (for the same objectID and same message type?), and the orderingStamp defines the sequence.

member.name: orderingStamp
member.text: This appears to count up for all message types.

member.name: serverID
member.text: This should match the id from the packet header for server to client. Client seems to leave this 0.

member.name: eventType
member.text: Flag values identifying the message properties

member.name: numFrags
member.text: The number of fragments that make up the full content. Partial fragments will always be sent alone and will fill the entire packet, except for the tail fragment. The tail fragment can be sent prior to the others if it will fit.

member.name: blobFragSize
member.text: Size of bytes contained in this fragment, including this header

member.name: blobNum
member.text: The zero based index of this fragment.

member.name: queueID
member.text: Identifies the queue this message should go into. Client (and seemingly Server too) maintains several different queues for processing messages. The queues seem to roughly align with overall feature type. Eg client maintains one for login, one for dat, one for 3d/world, and one for UI.

array.name: body
array.text: Body content of the fragment, containing a single message
